profile/whyBitcamp: I took some computer science programs in middle school. But, because the classes were poorly organized and the majority of students were not passionate about the subject, I was turned off to the field of computer science as a whole. On a whim, I decided to give the field a second chance last semester. Using Codecademy I began to relearn Python in my free time. Accomplishing projects, on my own, peaked my interest in the field I had initially sworn off years ago. This semester, I decided to take the introductory computer science course at my school. I had heard it would be a difficult course, but I was up for the challenge. So far, the class has been difficult at points, but it is one of the most rewarding courses I have ever taken so far. I believe that Bitcamp gives me the opportunity to delve deeper into computer science. I realize that if I want to continue as a computer science major, there is still much to learn. This hackathon presents a friendly environment to learn about a field I am passionate about along with peers with similar interests. It also gives me the chance to apply what I have learned to work towards creating something of my own. Additionally, the workshops provide places to gain an understanding on real-world applications to programming: through software development, VR, and similar areas. Bitcamp also presents an opportunity to improve my problem-solving skills, within the field of CIS. It will prepare me for my future in the computer science field, as I gain experience working with others, and alone, on projects.

profile/buildBitcamp:
As a budding programmer, what I hope to learn at Bitcamp are the skills needed to become a full-stack software engineer, not just in traditional front-end and back-end development but also how to integrate them together to create impactful software. As a person interested in data analytics and its implications in the tech industry, I also wish to gain knowledge on how to make sense of the different metrics in big data as I challenge myself to evolve as a data scientist in suited to deal with large information systems. 

I am also eager to expose myself to new programming languages and their associated platforms and build environments to further expand my horizons as a software engineer at Bitcamp. In particular, I am excited to gain invaluable experience in scripting languages and database management through the use of tools such as MongoDB, Angular, and Ruby so that I may use them to build exciting projects with diverse applications ranging from healthcare to virtual reality. Having been an attendee of a few hackathons, I also wish to enhance my coding skills beyond simple programs to be capable of developing software packages and gain a complete understanding of how these skills can be applied to solving real-world problems. Bitcamp is uniquely poised to facilitate this learning environment by providing an experience that allows me to not only exercise my skills to build awesome projects and tools with amazing people but also learn new insights from those people in reciprocal relationships.

As a software engineer interested in building application features, I believe that I have more flexibility to explore my technical skills and their implications through conscious design choices and the use of creative algorithms than if I would in the later stages of the software development cycle. Though I am capable of being independent by nature, I have learned from experience the benefits of having a mentor to guide me through the process. Brimming with exciting opportunities, Bitcamp can further unlock my potential as a coder by giving me the chance to express my passions into a project I love with all the wisdom a mentor can provide like no other. At the end of the day, what I want most is a communal environment where I am surrounded by creative and determined problem solvers. Bitcamp offers the ideal learning experience that I crave for beyond the scope of the classroom for innovative development of future technology solutions, and I am certain I will make the most of it.

profile/whyBitcamp:
My interest in computer science was first piqued my first year in the magnet program at Takoma Park Middle with the introduction of the programming unit and a required research project. In attempting to find an adequate topic, I came across the Raspberry Pi. Even as a newly released product, I was astonished by how much others had achieved using this pocket-sized machine. The next week of my life revolved solely on figuring out just how much this little device could do. That Friday I could hardly wait to share my newfound passion with my fellow classmates, coming in early in hopes of presenting first. From then on I pursued my technology education with a renewed sense of enthusiasm, becoming proficient in Python, JavaScript, Java, and C# and pulling apart computers to mentally put together how they work.
Computer science is one of the few fields that offers the potential to make a significant impact in just about every industry. Whether it be using Artificial Intelligence to improve upon existing human constructs, the Internet of Things and Cloud computing to help farmers improve efficiency, or Blockchain to track and secure transactions, computer science, in its many forms, is limited only by one’s imagination. With computer science, one can go from concept to market in just a couple weeks, often with minimal investment.

profile/buildBitcamp:
Many of my personal ambitions revolve around helping others and improving others’ quality of life. As such, I’ve always wanted to develop communication apps, allowing ease of access for a particular user base. For example, having an app that allows users to anonymously post certain health/fitness/medical concerns they might have, and other users can provide relevant input, whether they have experience with the same issue or simply recommend possible ailments to look up online. Furthermore, medical professionals can verify their degree, and a badge will display next to their names, giving them credibility to post suggested diagnoses/relevant courses of actions. 

I believe such an application will be very useful because often times people either don’t know where to start when it comes to a medical issue, or they’re simply paranoid about something that may potentially be harmless. Therefore, having an app that allows people to easily broadcast their situation to a large community and quickly gather a list of suggestions and recommendations will allow people to make wiser and more informed decisions when it comes to maintaining their health.

profile/buildBitcamp:
Questions that start with 'Why' are the most intriguing. I think with those questions are really the most thought-provoking ones out there. When people get too caught up in their daily actions and forget to ask ‘why am I doing this?’, that is when the real reason that one is doing something is forgotten. I think this happens a lot with college students who get so focused on doing well in their classes or the particular student organization that they are working on that they forget the real reason that they do what they do, no matter what it is. 
One interesting problem that’s on my mind has to do with a lot of times people need extra help whether that's an elderly person mowing their lawn, a small business owner getting ready for a packed weekend, or just a college student who needs help moving boxes. I think it would be really cool to be able to connect those people to the ones who are looking for extra cash and are ready to help. I’m super excited to try and help solve this gap in the world and hopefully develop an uber model for part-time work.
profile/whyBitcamp:
I really love the idea of immersion in a particular topic for 36 hours. In school, I'll be working on one project for a few hours and then have to go to a club meeting or do an assignment for a different class. I feel that the experience that I could get out of a hackathon is truly unique because when else are so many like-minded individuals together for a whole weekend to focus on the same major theme. I feel as if this environment of so many learners of similar fields all in one place could really spark something amazing. 
My hope is to leave bitcamp with a tangible functioning product. I want to be able to put my all into a program and be able to say that this my team's unique idea that we created and it does what we want it to do alleviating some inefficiency in the world.

profile/buildBitcamp: Not entirely sure yet but I plan to build a project where we deploy machine learning algorithms to end users through android apps or a reactive web application. I have a couple ideas already based on language processing and natural speech but these ideas will probably change. I also have a couple ideas related to computer vision or real time image processing apps. Some of the most important computer vision problems in my opinion are edge/object detection, scene recognition, and dense captioning. Object detection and dense captioning go closely together because creating dense captions (captioning every distinct object of the picture in sections) requires some knowledge of what makes up an object and requires segmenting the image into multiple objects. This interests me because there are lots of uses for this kind of algorithm, for example identifying scenes and creating more advanced filtering to search through huge databases of images and increasing the capacity of robots, including self driving cars to perform in real life scenarios.
profile/whyBitcamp: I am interested in attending BitCamp because I love the culture at hackathons and I want to meet new people and build something cool. I also want to attend a couple of the interesting workshops. I am also interested in improving my skills in actually building an application from start to finish. In the past, I have done research relating to hyperparameter optimization, creating a bioinformatics tool for antibody developability, and improving support vector machine resilience to outliers, but my most recent project that I’m still working on is about catastrophic forgetting. This time though, I am excited to take a step back from research and create actual applications that people will use.

This AI bot would read in the voicemail and use the Google Calendar API to see if I would be free at a certain time. profile/whyBitcamp:
I'm really interested in coming to Bitcamp because I've heard about how well it's run. I've become sort of disillusioned with some of the more competitive hackathons, and speaking with one of the former organizers of Bitcamp who was mentoring during HackNYU (which I'm was an organizer of this year) showed me a lot about how Bitcamp tries to be a different sort of experience with an entirely different philosophy. As an organizer of HackNYU, this really resonated with me, as we're trying to reframe and reexamine our goals our event as it grows in size. 

I'm also interested in coming to Bitcamp to learn new skills (computer vision? pytorch?) and meet other makers. My favorite aspect of hackathons are probably the people, and seeing what others are making. I feel like the energy of a hackathon lets anything be possible.

(also, the campfire logo is very cute)

profile/buildBitcamp: At Bitcamp, I'm planning to implement computer vision and machine learning algorithms to solve an everlasting business problem: business location vacancies. I want to build a system that can, give, live feed of an area, identify the amount of vacant spots that individuals can use, as well as identify occupied spots. This would be helpful across a variety of domains, such as businesses, public spaces, as well as many more locations. Imagine you want to go to your favorite family restaurant on Friday night, but you get there to see threes a 3 hour wait. With this vacancy identifying algorithm, businesses could provide live updates to customers on their websites, or on any other platform. This is the idea that I'm interested in implementing at Bitcamp.
profile/whyBitcamp: As an individual with growing interest in different fields of technology and computer science, I see hackathons as weekends full of grind, where I can work towards learning new things and using those concepts to solve problems as well as create solutions. As I've been recently working towards gaining knowledge of machine learning and computer vision, I see Bitcamp as an opportunity to apply my newly learned skills to identify an issue, and design a solution to it. I also see it as an opportunity to network with other hackers and learn from individuals who are experienced with machine learning and computer vision as I move along with my project. Not only that, but it's a great overall networking opportunity for meeting other hackers with similar interests, as well as a diverse range of people with completely different interests. For all these reasons, I want to attend bitcamp as an innovator.

profile/buildBitcamp: One interesting idea I had was to create some sort of music app that tackles or at least attempts to minimize the anxiety or mental stress of individuals. The app would include several playlists of calm music that heals individuals mentally and allows them to rest, meditate, and calm down from the stress they have been feeling. Users would be able to create their own account, make their own playlists, view others' playlists, star their favorites, and gain some more insight on what type of music soothes certain moods or individuals the most. As an individual who often listens to music to suppress my anxiety, and to relax from the stress that sometimes builds up in my mind, I think that an app like this would be very helpful for many. In regards to the technical aspect of developing this, as I am inexperienced with Android or iOS development, I would most likely create a web app and design the UI. I would use HTML, CSS, JS, PHP for the front-end and implement the Spotify Web API to scrape some songs and data regarding moods corresponding to different genres of music. Overall, developing this app would be an exciting challenge that I would take on at this hackathon with other amazing teammates.
profile/whyBitcamp: After attending a few hackathons this year, I've realized that I sincerely enjoy the atmosphere of innovation and creation in these hackathons, which I gain fuel from to motivate me to create amazing things as well. From viewing the recap video of 2018, I would be so thrilled to join Bitcamp as all the fun activities and snacks that are provided would be a perfect way for my team and me to take meaningful breaks and bond over an event-filled, memorable weekend. As a relatively new hacker, Bitcamp would give me the chance to explore many topics and tools in the tech industry that I have yet to touch upon such as machine learning, AI, blockchain, etc. I am also quite intrigued by the Compass Challenge, as I have always had a mindset encompassing the importance of developing projects that serve some sort of purpose. The past few design and programming projects that I've worked on always involved developing something practical and beneficial to users. Most recently, I developed a web app called OutWeather that told users details on the weather as well as an outfit to wear based on the local weather and their fashion preferences. Overall, being apart of a huge hackathon of 1200+ hackers  in a crazy sports venue would be such a memorable experience, and an atmosphere that I would never forget.

profile/buildBitcamp:
I'm planning to build a malware analysis, forensics, and reverse engineering tool that for the moment I'll call Modality. This tool will have a variety of features. For assisting the malware analyst, the tool will build a 3D graph of possible execution paths, identified using a symbolic execution engine, so the analyst can see a summary of what this malware will do under certain circumstances.  In addition, the tool will analyze conditional branches, system calls, and library calls in order to classify different operations semantically. This will allow it to, for example, print a PDF with a simple summary of what the program does under different conditions. I have ideas for other features, including visualizing file entropy (to look for encrypted segments or code patterns), dealing with obfuscation, looking for dead code, etc.

All this will be unified under a simple GUI, so one doesn't have to have much technical ability to use it. For example, a user might "File -> open sample", and the click "print summary", and will get a pdf detailing the malware behavior. The more advanced options are available for the technically skilled.

profile/buildBitcamp: My idea has been something I have been pursuing over a few hackathons in small portions that I pitch as stand-alone apps. I want Bitcamp to be another opportunity that will allow me to showcase my idea. Essentially, it is a web application that attempts to solve the weak dissemination of information on our large campus. The First Look Fair is a small yearly event and clubs and events have no advertising power on campus due to how large it is. In addition, new students themselves have difficulty finding clubs and organizations they are passionate it as a byproduct. My solution will centralize college data on clubs and organizations and match students to their very own custom feed in order to provide them the best college experience. The feed will be unique and never repetitive in order to allow students to see a lot of relevant activities that are happening on campus. Dubbed UNITE, I hope this product will one day become a huge idea that revolutionizes college campuses everywhere.

I've always had this idea to create something that can translate body movement/body gestures into words to assist patients who are unable to communicate in a standard way (with language, ASL, etc). This could be targeted with patients suffering from dementia, or even people temporarily unable to speak.

I received this idea in high school at a Women in Tech conference when one of the speakers said she would love to see something applicable in this way at a hackathon. I've been thinking about the idea ever since. It has always seemed like a big project, but I've always wanted to explore it.

I realized that I could make a game out of this, by developing a glove controller that can detect when a finger bends and when a surface is tapped. Then, I could use those inputs to make a rhythm game that is completely independent of a bulky controller, only requiring a glove and a surface. I plan to build this glove as well as an app to interpret the inputs from the glove and allow the user play a simple game.

profile/buildBitcamp: I'm open to anything, but I'd love to do something related to AI and self-learning. In January I helped create an API for another hackathon (DeltaHacks) that detects whether vehicles (specifically commercial trucks) are being stolen based on the inputs of location and time-based data from trackers located in these trucks. While we were successful, It is very difficult to pinpoint something fishy happening with all the very normal data provided, and as the information provided inevitably becomes more reliable and specific, the algorithm that checks this information should be improved as well, which got me thinking about what a self-learning API would look like for problems like this. profile/buildBitcamp: I want to create something that empowers women. My sorority had a sisterhood appreciation event where we allowed each other to compliment other sisters. We sent out a Google form, and sisters filled out the compliment for their intended recipient. Then, these compliments were printed out onto cute paper cards and handed out to the intended recipient during chapter. All the sisters really enjoyed this small gesture. I myself received a card that said "Thank you for always having a reason to smile." It was anonymous, but it honestly made my week that someone thought that of me. profile/whyBitcamp:
I've found that hackathons are an awesome way to meet passionate and disciplined people. I'm extremely passionate about UX design, and I want to meet other fellow designers, as well as developers, PMs and business people to collaborate with and make a vision come to life. Seeing an idea go from conception to final prototype is incredibly satisfying. For me, hackathons are where the magic happens. 

My team won for Best Overall Hack at Cornell’s Fintech Hackathon last semester. We wanted to help micro-entrepreneurs deposit and maintain money in their savings account. To do so, we used predictive analysis (forecasting how much you could save in 10 years if you put a certain amount of money in your account now) and gamification (using a points reward and lottery system) to incentivize human behavior. I attribute our success to our teamwork and creativity, and I want to have a similar experience at Bitcamp. I've definitely heard a lot of great things about this hackathon, and since this is my last year in school, I would love to attend.

profile/buildBitcamp: I would like to build a health application. I know there are already many, but the difference with this one (called Posihealth right now) is that it is not weight loss/ calorie centered at all. I did some research and found that the overwhelming majority of "health" apps are focused on counting calories and weight loss. I think that the idea that weight loss equals health is extremely toxic and absolutely not healthy, so I want to work on my own. I have also found that most health apps only talk about physical health, when mental health is just as important, so I would like to build an application that includes mental health information and help as well. 1 Feature Matching and Outlier rejection using RANSAC

profile/buildBitcamp: Though I have many ideas in the works, I would love to build a project centered around Das Marsprojekt (The Mars Project) by Wernher Von Braun. The book is essentially a technical "guide" for a manned mission to Mars. I would like to create an application that calculates the accuracy of his predictions based on data from Mars missions so far (Curiosity, InSight, etc.).
profile/whyBitcamp: I'm so excited that Bitcamp includes some hardware hacking alongside programming. I would love to check out the Hardware Village and get some experience and advice with the mentors there. Also, Bitcamp generally seems so well-established and planned. I'm excited to meet people who enjoy building and coding who aren't from Boulder!
